759. Ter7·etque—-avis; the punishment of Phineus, of being deprived of sight, and having his sood defiled by the Harpyes, on account of his having revealed the future to men, is well known. According to another version of this myth, Phineus, at the instance of his second wife Idaea, deprived his sons by his first mar- riage of their sight, for which crime he afterwards suf- fered the same punishment in the infernal regions, which, according to the more familiar story, was in· flicted upon him during his lisetime.
